All are beasts in the end.

We are all the architects of the system in which we find ourselves trapped. The system promises our liberation through progress and logic but in reality this is a fallacy thinly disguising the true nature of anarchy. Here we see the hollowed promise of logic, faith and pragmatism to save us from ourselves. I have a recurring dream of hell and it looks something like this.

A unique cinematic take on Tragedy of being a woman in Iranian society. A universal theme has been carried out since the beginning without being trapped in a particularly pointed storyline. The circle tells bitter stories about the lives of several women in Tehran, and it does so in an almost documentary manner, without having a formal structure.

35mm, rewatched. Mostly consisting of sequence-shots by hand-held camera, admirably consistent and persistent, without the sudden variations of re-frames and focuses that characterize much of the current cinema, often the camera stops and fixes itself, giving us visual transposition framings of a dramatic immensity - see the conversation between two women at a box office, framed behind a grid: particular is general.

Incredible film.

It has a few good moments, no doubt. Beautiful photography too, I'll give it that. Kinda reminds me of The GoodTimesKid; difference being that while I'll recommend that to anyone and everyone I know, I wouldn't this film. I'm sorry, but for the most part, this was boring as fuck.

Through the film's form and soundscape, Guerin leads viewers to believe that his camera and boom mic merely observe daily life. However, if one probes further, it becomes evident that the film wears many layers of intricate construction, from the meticulous sound design to the world class cinematography. I am very glad that I had a chance to rewatch this.

Es un film con vida propia, acerca de un joven dibujante que pasa el día sentado en un café de Estrasburgo, observando, reflexionando, añorando a Sylvia, una mujer que conoció años atrás, en esa búsqueda, centra su mirada a las cuantiosas mujeres que caminan, charlan y están a su alrededor. 
Gran parte del film transcurre en el recorrido de ésta busqueda, muy nostálgica y sensiblera. 

9/10

beautiful town,(strassbourg) beautiful young people, beautiful film. it invites the viewer to revel with the characters in the sheer wonderous beauty of everyday goings on. a minor masterpiece that i can't seem to stop thinking about.

Kurosawa's worst movie, a look into the lives of damaged, odd poor people who reside in the slums. The characters are caricatures. It is a great film, but I must have missed the narrative holding it together. Or maybe these isn't, and we just have to deal with a bunch of characters going about their lives. The train, ( tram?) Miming kid is great and so are the women around the water point.

Like Godzilla emerging from the sea, the successor of 'Red Beard' seems to surface from Japan's collective unconscious – a monstruous dreamscape of poverty, depravity and mental illness. For a long time I considered it a rather abstract take on human misery, but Shigero Mizuki's 'Showa' made me realize there is far more realism involved than I thought.
35mm, seen in 1993,rated from memory. Cinematography by Takao Saitô and Yasumichi Fukuzawa.

Kurosawa’s first color film looks like a kid took several bright crayons and drew a fantasy land. Except the film takes place in a shantytown outside of Toyko, with characters so trapped and doomed that there’s not much to hold onto. Kurosawa is one of the greatest humanists, but it’s difficult to find any humanity in the bleak plain he created here.

Kurosawa achieves the desperate atmosphere but not the message of innate happiness represented by vibrant color usage. The result is a cheerful attempt to demonstrate a mechanism of suffering from bad faith, and a large section of it has faded out. incapable construction of image to obtain imaginary happiness and negligence of parallel reality would describe and deconstruct both the film and its characters.
OMFG THIS IS SUCH A BEAUTIFUL FILM!!!

Kurosawa's first color film marks a clear more experimental style, and while not all of it worked it honestly fascinated me nonetheless. It's borderline creepy and nightmarish, and Kurosawa fully utilized the use of colors.

The effect can be odd & disengaging, but entirely unique. The only thing more dazzling than Kurosawa's experiments with colour, light & composition is the sensitivity he shows to his characters.

It displays his characteristic desire to explore the nature of humanity and in this case, humanity in desperation.  Could definitely see the Dostoyevsky influence here

Absolutely sublime humanistic cinema as always from Kurosawa. Perhaps one of my favourite of his gendaigeki films, there are scenes which make your heart ache, your anger boil, your faith in humanity die and then resurrect all in the same scene, bloody wonderful stuff.

In retrospect, it's easy to see why this was a commercial failure when it was released, and the performances don't help much, as many of the actors mug for all they're worth. Still, for a Kurosawa fan, this is worth watching just to see him play with colour and light on a new style of canvas for the first time, and the film's gentle humanism lingers after it's over.

Good intentions don't make good movies. Kurosawa really wasn's thinking at all, as this is a picture about nothing, full of breath-taking images that really reflect an absence of thought about anything other than a sort of naive conception of "cinematic expressionism".There's no life in the shots and the movie never costructs its own time. All we have left is a sentimental, boring movie about people living in slums.

The first hour was incredibly uneven, but eventually it felt as if Kurosawa finally found his footing and the end result is very beautiful, moving at times and incredibly humanistic. The colors and production design were just out of this world and for a first color effort, this is just amazing to look at. Despite it's flaws, it's human moments remind me of why Kurosawa is my all time favorite filmmaker.
I didn't have high expectations for this film but I thought it was really beautiful, human, and powerful, another great Kurosawa film.

I thought it was a surprisingly detached drama coming from Kurosawa's storytelling standards, I was glad to see him so uninvolved in creating pathos and focusing more on multiple character studies that in the end may not get the proper treatment, but that amounts to a highly original and memorable approach to one of his usual subjects. Catherine Deneuve is a delight as Marion! In my opinion, this film is all about Marion and the secrets she hides, the challenges she faces taking over her husband's theatre, and the careful manoeuvring she must do to stay in the good opinion of the cast, the audience, the key critic, and the Germans. The film centres around the daily tension of the time rather than big dramatic events.
Compleja e intrigante. Mantiene la tensión durante todo el relato. Como es común en Truffaut, hace gala de actuaciones bien logradas y un montaje impecable.

Haughty stylistic aplomb and refinement of the Truffaut's handiwork reaches its summit in a surrepticiously multilayered piece that ruminates the nature of paralysis - corporeal, ideological, municipal and above all spiritual as the proverbial serpent of zeitgeist constricts ideals, desires, will and minds and challenges them to absolute stillness amidst the storm of ultimately transient status quo.

The first time I’ve read Alexandre Astrue’s manifesto for the New Wave and met the “camera-stylo” I did not understand what he meant by it. But it was watching Truffaut’s film that I finally grasped the meaning of the camera-stylo: it was when I could not describe Truffaut but with “poetry”, that I realized that poetry is a written genre and I was using this adjective to describe a filme. That’s Truffaut: pure poetry

Crafty camera work moving beautifully within restricted spaces - nice reflection of Hitchcock on Truffaut. Depardieu was failure - he was convincing neither being a resistance fighter nor a womanizer. Plot also might have been more witty - it had all the possibilities. But still a beautiful watch.

An amazing choice by Truffaut by showing us the occupation by the view of the artists at the time. A game of violence and concession in order to preserve their job, but also fight for their liberty. I think there's a funny reference for Vittorio de Sica's "Bicycle Thieves" when Bernard tells his bicycle story. The recriation of the 40's is also very good. I'd definitely say it's among Truffaut's bests.

Maravilhoso! Muito diferente do Truffaut de Doinel e também da linguagem dos filmes baseados em romances — o que mostra toda sua versatilidade. Se por um lado há aqui todos seus traços — a tragédia amorosa, a importância de um narrador onisciente —, ele também cria uma nova forma de construí-los (a tragédia é a guerra, sobretudo). E há um aspecto novo: sua francesidade à toda carga. Sem contar Catherine Deneuve.

Belíssimo filme que ressalta a força da arte na Resistência francesa. Truffaut mostra a atmosfera de tensão criada pela ocupação da França pelos nazistas e expressa a peculiaridade e a indignação dos franceses durante a ocupação. A cena em que o ator espanca o jornalista adepto do nazismo é exemplo disso. Deneuve  e Depardieu estão maravilhosos na arte de interpretar o palco e a vida real ao mesmo tempo.

Despite being set during the war, the film jostles with heavy issues with such lightness, as you’d expect from Truffaut. Instead of becoming melancholic, like the era it represents, and depicting the horrors of war, it is instead a film about how art gave meaning to people’s lives during WW2. Very beautiful indeed.
Really like the 1940s French setting,it’s is a dark time of French in history.
Great treatment of the dangers for those in the performing arts, especially Jews, in the lives of occupied Paris during World War II.

The Last Metro marries French New Wave with the French 'prestige picture', with stars from the two respective eras (Deneuve and Depardieu) staging a play while Paris is in the shadow of the Occupation. The Paris of TLM is both warm and dangerous, with Resistance fighters hiding in alleys and the Gestapo breaking into cellars. Classically Hitchockian in its approach, The Last Metro is enchanting and justly celebrated.
Simples e belo.
Well worth its reputation as a classic of French cinema, Deneuve and Depardieu give outstanding performances supported by the whole cast in an exquisite tale of wartime occupied Paris.

Its romanticized narrative style contrasts powerfully with the gravity of its subject: the multifarious paths that man can follow in the struggle for survival.

A self-consciously theatrical film about WWII, which makes perfect sense because it's about characters who, in one way or another, use theater as a hideout from the war. Maybe it's because Truffaut loved Children of Paradise, maybe it's an attempt to grapple with a desire to be more diverting than political—the artistic process as its own salvation. Circa 1980, Godard was more interesting. But Truffaut was more fun.

The Last Metro takes you behind the stage of a theater in German occupation of France. The title refers to the practice under which Parisians theaters ended shows in time for audiences to catch trains home before the curfew. An inspiring film that conjures history and drama in a theater troupe.

A near perfect movie at least visually and in the acting department as it is hard not to be absorbed by the spectacle and setting of a theater trying to survive in occupied WW2 France. Not so sure if the story manages to really fullfill all it could accomplish with it's marvellous build-up though, but what we get is still gripping and memorable.

Toying intelligently with artifice it still glows with its grace and with a controlled handling of mood in weaving together biography and history.

This is a brilliant war film expertly directed by Rossellini and beautifully acted by De Sica. It shows the lengths people will go through to help others even if they are not capable of doing so and then the ultimate consequence that people initially pay for their actions.

An interesting choice for my first Rossellini, I'm sure, but I was far too intrigued at the prospect of the great Vittorio De Sica in the lead role. His performance is both heartbreaking and bleak, and yet there is warmth to him. Truly remarkable war story.
Dude
Ultimately, as powerful as any of his earlier war films. In its own quiet way, perhaps even more so.

A really offbeat World War II drama, even for Rossellini.  The director eschews his signature neo-realism (think Open City) for artificial backdrops that allow him to tell his story of shifting alliances and redemption. He humanizes his characters -- not only De Sica's grifter but also the German colonel who shows war-weary empathy. The only fault: The ending, while grisly, is a bit jingoistic.

If the cinematography is more formal than usual for Rossellini, it works well with the gravity provided by De Sica's performance. The effect is ceremonial, as though we're watching a great Shakespearian tragedy.

A masterpiece from Roberto Rossellini. 
 Trying to survive the German Occupation Of Italy -1943-1945. Vittorio De Sica is brilliant as a flawed character who pulls himself up due to the expectations of others.
15 years after the allied victory over fascist Italy seemed proper time to do some justice with this masterpiece! Sadly now the allies are the invaders and we are to face a complex dejavu.

De Sica is, as always, magnetic. Rossellini is, as always, sublime. Another beautiful exposition by Europe's post-war generation. This is a straight forward character study that pits brutality against frailty, principle against the raw will to survive. We can only hope that one day our artists will examine the post-911 world with such sensitivity.

3.8 The story is ordinary and melodramatic, but the way it is told is exciting and original. The 'fading out' of characters at the end of a scene is quite astonishing, so is the art deco-design of most of the film's architecture. Shimizu always surprises me and broadens my clichéd image of Japanese cinema.

Modernista en su acercamiento a través de una rigurosa escritura de espacios compuestos por movimientos laterales, simetrías, planos y contraplanos. Melancólicamente escenificada, pues el drama social de la prostitución, representado sin la potencia emocional de los posteriores Mizoguchi y Naruse, es proyectado hacia el interior bajo gestos sutiles. Un triunfo en sus yuxtaposiciones de signos (objetos y emociones).
Another solid cinematic achievement that is strangely different from the rest of Shimizu's works.

One thing early/silent Japanese cinema suffered from was standard cinematography, but Shimizu takes a fairly simple story and raises the bar with a lyrical visual style, capturing the heart of its characters, era and city. The most visually ambitious film of 1933.

Nothing anyone could write about Monsieur Verdoux, could possibly stack up to what André Bazin wrote, so I'm not even gonna try. Let's just say that after Chaplin's Great Dictator humanist speech fell on deaf ears, and the horrors of World War II were laid bare, Charlie couldn't do anything but transform the Tramp into a reflexion of this awful world; hypocrite, unscrupulous, and apologetic of murder.

When I first saw ARSENIC AND OLD LACE as a kid, I was aware, though not sophisticated, that the considerable pleasure afforded was of a highly perverse nature. Chaplin channels this exact thing as Verdoux, seducer-killer. The terms "sex act" or "act of murder" inidicate an event situated in time, but they also evoke playacting. The space of tension "before the act" becomes for Chaplin a theatre of moral calculus.

Verdoux' character is a moral riddle. He is fulll of contradictions - a remorseless serial killer with a kind heart, funny, likeable, in front of the guillotine a real philosopher. How could he exploit and kill? I see this 1947 film as a parable for the credibility breakdown of the "handrails" for life (Arendt) after Fascism and the Shoah, where people have made careers from the war without being hold accountable.

In the end it is more entertaining than the famous, but also pathetic comedies that are played up and down again and again. The irrational sociopathic film hero seems more lifelike than the idealistic tramp of early films.
